        "timestamp": "2020-08-04 12:49:53.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(1 comment)\n\nConfiguration properties we have been using policy/common code for this, this review introduces another way of doing configuration??\n\nIs this only for apex native policies? What about our other policy types, both native and non-native?",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "d77a3f0d60a2de912222826d4597bc5a06ef3e6f",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 5565,
          "name": "Andr� Schmid",
          "display_name": "André Schmid",
          "email": "andre.schmid@est.tech",
          "username": "andre.schmid"
        },
        "author_role": "OWNER",
        "timestamp": "2020-08-04 13:32:50.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(1 comment)\n\n> Patch Set 1:\n> \n> (1 comment)\n> \n> Configuration properties we have been using policy/common code for this, this review introduces another way of doing configuration??\n> \n> Is this only for apex native policies? What about our other policy types, both native and non-native?\n\nAbout the configuration, yes, it is introducing another way to do it because I didn't know there was already a way to do it. Please, could you show me some example I could follow?\n\nThis is only for the APEX Editor GUI. It is allowing to upload a policy file created in that interface to a configured endpoint. It is reusing part of the Download feature already present, that gives the user a JSON file, and uses the same idea of the apex-pdp/auth/cli-editor to parse the JSON to TOSCA before uploading it.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
      {
        "id": "e31dfabddb97df74742be65cd9f8a7bea144e965",
        "author": {
          "account_id": 811,
          "name": "Jim Hahn",
          "display_name": null,
          "email": "jrh3@att.com",
          "username": "jrh3"
        },
        "author_role": "REVIEWER",
        "timestamp": "2020-08-04 13:58:09.000000000",
        "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n(1 comment)\n\n> Patch Set 1:\n> \n> (1 comment)\n> \n> > Patch Set 1:\n> > \n> > (1 comment)\n> > \n> > Configuration properties we have been using policy/common code for this, this review introduces another way of doing configuration??\n> > \n> > Is this only for apex native policies? What about our other policy types, both native and non-native?\n> \n> About the configuration, yes, it is introducing another way to do it because I didn't know there was already a way to do it. Please, could you show me some example I could follow?\n> \n> This is only for the APEX Editor GUI. It is allowing to upload a policy file created in that interface to a configured endpoint. It is reusing part of the Download feature already present, that gives the user a JSON file, and uses the same idea of the apex-pdp/auth/cli-editor to parse the JSON to TOSCA before uploading it.\n\nAll of the configuration classes are found in policy/common.  Usage examples can be found in apex-pdp - just look for ParameterGroup.  Besides ParameterGroup, there's another mechanism, BeanValidator, that uses annotations to specify valid values within a data structure.  Examples of its use can be found in policy/models.\n\nBoth of the above build upon ValidationResult, which provides a way to identify one or more problems within a hierarchical property set.",
        "patchset_number": 1
      },
